00:13:35.370 --> 00:13:40.190
And how many of you are just
thinking about building one?

00:13:40.190 --> 00:13:42.050
OK, so it's already
convinced people.

00:13:42.050 --> 00:13:43.470
OK, good.

00:13:43.470 --> 00:13:46.470
So you're probably familiar
with this interface, which,

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:48.540
like a lot of
other devices, like

00:13:48.540 --> 00:13:51.615
streaming devices in the market
is what we call app-centric,

00:13:51.615 --> 00:13:53.490
which means that really
the app as the center

00:13:53.490 --> 00:13:55.020
of the experience.

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:57.310
But since we launched
Android TV three years ago,

00:13:57.310 --> 00:14:01.620
we realized that
things were changing,

00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:05.190
and user were consuming
entertainment differently

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:06.700
in their living room.

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:09.480
Well, of course, we
realized that the user

00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:10.890
gets more and more content.

00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:12.840
They have more and
more content available.

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:15.120
And it's increasingly
difficult for them

00:14:15.120 --> 00:14:17.070
to make a decision
on what to watch.

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:20.580
They have to compare
content sources from live TV

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:23.700
to [? SVO ?] to TiVo to UGC.

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:26.610
And also compare
content providers.

00:14:26.610 --> 00:14:29.340
Go into the app, browse
the content, going out

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:32.970
and change providers, it's
increasingly difficult.

00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:36.960
This is why, with Android's
O, we have completely

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:41.270
redefined the experience on
the home screen of Android TV.

00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:43.950
We made it channel-based.

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:47.050
But more importantly, we
made it content-centric.

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:50.010
This means that we're giving
more and more prominence

00:14:50.010 --> 00:14:53.760
to your content in the
discovery experience.

00:14:53.760 --> 00:14:57.030
We basically want the user
to spend more time watching

00:14:57.030 --> 00:15:00.870
your content, as opposed
to simply looking for it's.

00:15:00.870 --> 00:15:02.970
Not only do we think that
this will significantly

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:04.710
improve discovery.

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:07.530
We also think that this
will impact positively

00:15:07.530 --> 00:15:11.040
the way you're going to
reengage with your users.

00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:16.150
To get them to come back to
your app and watch your content.

00:15:16.150 --> 00:15:18.270
So let's take a
closer look at it.

00:15:18.270 --> 00:15:20.730
So at the top, you
have quick access

00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:23.340
to the search
functionality, which

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:27.420
now becomes Google Assistant,
as Serge was explaining.

00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:30.090
Just below, you have
the favorite app row,

00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:34.290
which basically allows users to
launch into their favorite app

00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:35.430
really quickly.

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:40.260
On the right, a red button,
which is basically the app

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:43.300
view page, which includes
all the apps that

00:15:43.300 --> 00:15:46.400
are installed into the device.

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:48.570
But here is where it
becomes interesting.

00:15:48.570 --> 00:15:54.040
Continuing down, we had several
rows that we call channels.

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:56.340
These channels are
made of cards that we

00:15:56.340 --> 00:16:00.240
call programs, that basically
give maximum prominence

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:01.830
to your content.

00:16:01.830 --> 00:16:06.510
These channels are the core of
the new home screen experience.

00:16:06.510 --> 00:16:10.110
Each developer will be able
to create his own channel

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:13.080
and benefit from a
greater real estate

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:15.240
to promote their content.

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:19.110
When a user selects one
program, well, obviously ,

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:21.990
it launches the app
and immediately starts

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:23.010
the playback.

00:16:23.010 --> 00:16:25.140
But interestingly,
if the user decides

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:28.050
to press the Back button,
instead of coming back

00:16:28.050 --> 00:16:30.450
to the homepage of
Android TV it will

00:16:30.450 --> 00:16:33.480
be taken to a higher-level
screen of your app

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:36.480
and continue browsing
within your own app.

00:16:39.210 --> 00:16:41.267
As a developer, of course,
you have full control

00:16:41.267 --> 00:16:42.600
of what you put in your channel.

00:16:42.600 --> 00:16:44.670
You can decide
what content you're

00:16:44.670 --> 00:16:47.580
going to put, what programs
you're going to put,

00:16:47.580 --> 00:16:49.800
what order you
want to show them,

00:16:49.800 --> 00:16:52.620
all the content metadata,
as well as the channel

00:16:52.620 --> 00:16:55.350
names and the branding.

00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:57.990
One of the features
I'm more excited about

00:16:57.990 --> 00:17:02.250
is video previews that are
played, as you can see here,

00:17:02.250 --> 00:17:06.119
whenever one particular
program is on focus.

00:17:06.119 --> 00:17:08.970
As a developer,
you can decide what

00:17:08.970 --> 00:17:12.950
to include in this video
preview, like live TV.

00:17:12.950 --> 00:17:17.369
Either trailers
or video previews.

00:17:17.369 --> 00:17:20.400
By default, only
one primary channel

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:23.700
will be displayed into
the Android TV interface.

00:17:23.700 --> 00:17:25.440
But as a developer,
you can decide

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:29.940
to add additional channels
that the user will

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:32.470
be able to add into
their interface

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:34.480
according to their preferences.

00:17:34.480 --> 00:17:37.140
So let's say you are, for
example, a pay TV provider,

00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:41.520
and you create a primary channel
that aggregates all the best

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:43.060
content you have.

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:44.880
You can also think
about creating

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:49.170
additional secondary channels
based on specific topics,

00:17:49.170 --> 00:17:53.370
like sports, kids' content,
or series that the user will

00:17:53.370 --> 00:17:56.190
be able to add
into his interface,

00:17:56.190 --> 00:17:58.940
according to his preferences.

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:01.250
So as mentioned
earlier, Android TV

00:18:01.250 --> 00:18:03.240
is, of course, about discovery.

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:05.540
The new Android TV home
is about discovery,

00:18:05.540 --> 00:18:08.600
but it's also a lot
about re-engagement.

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:11.630
We really want to make
sure that your user can

00:18:11.630 --> 00:18:15.740
come back to your app and
consume that content again

00:18:15.740 --> 00:18:17.000
and again.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:21.350
This is why we created what
we call the watch next row.

00:18:21.350 --> 00:18:24.830
All the content that the user
has been previously engaged

00:18:24.830 --> 00:18:28.940
with will be consolidated,
aggregated into this watch

00:18:28.940 --> 00:18:33.470
next channel that will always
appear in second position

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:36.380
below the favorite app row.

00:18:36.380 --> 00:18:40.804
Studies show that a large
majority of watched sessions

00:18:40.804 --> 00:18:44.240
are links to
previously-engaged content.

00:18:44.240 --> 00:18:46.400
And this is the whole
thinking around it.

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:50.000
As a developer, this will
help you drive re-engagement

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.200
and improve your retention,
as your content will

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:57.300
be seen in this channel
whenever, for example,

00:18:57.300 --> 00:19:01.130
a user plays a video
and doesn't finish it,

00:19:01.130 --> 00:19:05.600
or a new episode of a
series is newly available,

00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:08.150
or just simply because the
user can add your content

00:19:08.150 --> 00:19:11.570
into the watch list.

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:14.180
So in the previous
two sections, we

00:19:14.180 --> 00:19:18.470
gave you an overview of the most
recent evolution of Android TV.

00:19:18.470 --> 00:19:21.170
If you think about it,
both Google Assistant

00:19:21.170 --> 00:19:23.630
and the new Android
TV home screen

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:26.630
aim at improving
discoverability of the content,

00:19:26.630 --> 00:19:29.840
but more importantly,
re-engagement longer-term

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:32.420
with your existing customers.

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:35.318
But beyond these two
platform evolutions,

00:19:35.318 --> 00:19:37.692
there are a lot of things that
you can do inside your app

00:19:37.692 --> 00:19:39.920
in order to improve
the experience.

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:42.770
But remember, as
a form factor, TV

00:19:42.770 --> 00:19:46.550
is unique in the way
we interact with it.

00:19:46.550 --> 00:19:49.670
The use of a remote control
makes it often quite tedious

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:52.100
and difficult to navigate.

00:19:52.100 --> 00:19:54.950
This means that you should
pay even more attention

00:19:54.950 --> 00:19:56.810
to making sure that
the experience is

00:19:56.810 --> 00:20:01.100
as frictionless as possible
at each critical point

00:20:01.100 --> 00:20:03.260
of your user journey.

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:10.080
So typically, identification,
discovery, and payment.

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:12.470
So let's start with
authentication.

00:20:12.470 --> 00:20:15.800
While identification
is obviously

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:18.080
a precondition for
the personalization

00:20:18.080 --> 00:20:20.900
of your experience
inside of your app,

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:24.080
it's also a critical moment
where developers, like you,

00:20:24.080 --> 00:20:26.339
lose a lot of users.

00:20:26.339 --> 00:20:28.130
That's why we introduced,
a couple of years

00:20:28.130 --> 00:20:31.600
ago, Smart Lock for passwords in
order to remove this friction.

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:34.670
So by integrating with
Smart Lock for passwords,

00:20:34.670 --> 00:20:37.700
you can automatically
sign up users

00:20:37.700 --> 00:20:40.610
into your app using the
credential that they

00:20:40.610 --> 00:20:44.840
have already saved on other
Android devices, or on Chrome.

00:20:44.840 --> 00:20:49.190
So in this example with
myCanal, it has automatically

00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:52.430
recognized and logged in
the user that was accessing

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:54.870
the app for the first time.

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:57.410
This is especially
relevant knowing that,

00:20:57.410 --> 00:21:00.590
as we said, during the
identification process

00:21:00.590 --> 00:21:03.650
on TV with a remote control
is particularly painful.

00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:08.570
So now, let's talk
about discovery.

00:21:08.570 --> 00:21:11.810
As we all know, discovery
is a very complex process

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:16.850
that involves internal, external
factors that will determine

00:21:16.850 --> 00:21:18.290
what the user wants to watch.

00:21:18.290 --> 00:21:22.580
But also, how precise is the
idea of what you want to watch.

00:21:22.580 --> 00:21:25.430
So if you're
commuting, it won't be

00:21:25.430 --> 00:21:28.280
similar to if you are
nicely, comfortably

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:29.900
sitting on your sofa.

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:31.160
How much time do you have?

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:33.450
How many people are part
of the watching group?

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:36.530
Your mood and your mindset
at a particular time

00:21:36.530 --> 00:21:39.980
will determine
directly the discovery,

00:21:39.980 --> 00:21:42.590
and position you
differently in what

00:21:42.590 --> 00:21:44.325
we call the certainty spectrum.

00:21:47.020 --> 00:21:50.070
So across the industry,
research tells us

00:21:50.070 --> 00:21:53.430
that when deciding
what to watch,

00:21:53.430 --> 00:21:57.390
the user operates in four
different modalities.

00:21:57.390 --> 00:22:01.570
Find, select, browse, and surf.

00:22:01.570 --> 00:22:04.260
Often, people can jump from
one modality to the other.

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:06.750
Like as soon as, for example,
some content finishes,

00:22:06.750 --> 00:22:10.290
or a new person comes into
the watching group, etc.

00:22:10.290 --> 00:22:12.000
But the goal for
you is to make sure

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.840
that your app addresses
each of these modalities

00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:18.090
with a minimum effort.

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:20.430
So let's start with search.

00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:24.540
We estimate that's
around 20% of the viewing

00:22:24.540 --> 00:22:27.910
comes from a search
functionality.

00:22:27.910 --> 00:22:30.150
So that means that
you should really,

00:22:30.150 --> 00:22:34.050
there's real value for you
to make sure that this works.

00:22:34.050 --> 00:22:36.990
Beyond content and titles,
you should make sure

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:40.200
that the search
functionality also

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:43.740
takes into account all your
metadata, such as actors,

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:47.400
categories, genres, etc., etc.

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:50.244
Are you able to address
and solve queries?

00:22:50.244 --> 00:22:51.660
We realize that a
lot of users are

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:54.630
making queries that actually
don't lead to any results.

00:22:54.630 --> 00:22:56.520
There's something to
be done around this.

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:59.730
Also, could you improve the
search experience using what

00:22:59.730 --> 00:23:02.010
we call natural
language processing,

00:23:02.010 --> 00:23:06.330
in order to make the
experience even more natural.

00:23:06.330 --> 00:23:09.570
Similarly, make sure that
the user has the ability

00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:14.370
to access his favorite content
with functionality such as DVR,

00:23:14.370 --> 00:23:16.800
watch list, or add to favorites.

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:21.420
And moving down to the
certainty spectrum,

00:23:21.420 --> 00:23:24.270
there are different ways
to inspire your users

00:23:24.270 --> 00:23:25.710
so they can find their content.

00:23:25.710 --> 00:23:30.850
The usage of most popular
collection, content, category,

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:33.150
genre, etc., etc.

00:23:33.150 --> 00:23:35.070
And even more
editorial collections

00:23:35.070 --> 00:23:37.770
that can really inspire
the user in what to watch.

00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:39.800
So think about all these
different modalities,

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:41.883
and think within your app
what you can do in order

00:23:41.883 --> 00:23:44.900
to address each of them.

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:46.720
So once the user
shows some interest

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:48.670
in a particular
content, you want

00:23:48.670 --> 00:23:50.800
to make sure that
he also has access

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:52.960
to all the relevant
information that

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:57.060
would help me take the decision
to actually watch this content.

00:23:57.060 --> 00:23:58.480
So, of course, title.

00:23:58.480 --> 00:24:01.570
Also, a short and
long description.

00:24:01.570 --> 00:24:06.250
Don't undermine the importance
of beautiful images and video

00:24:06.250 --> 00:24:08.020
trailers.

00:24:08.020 --> 00:24:11.380
Finally, third-party
ratings, review

00:24:11.380 --> 00:24:15.887
are also critical when it
comes to taking a decision.

00:24:15.887 --> 00:24:17.470
Another aspect that
I find interesting

00:24:17.470 --> 00:24:22.030
is this idea of making
your experience even more

00:24:22.030 --> 00:24:23.410
linear inside your app.

00:24:23.410 --> 00:24:29.050
So the benefits of on-demand
consumption is undeniable.

00:24:29.050 --> 00:24:33.150
People are no longer forced
to come back to their house,

00:24:33.150 --> 00:24:35.890
rush into their living room to
watch their favorite program.

00:24:35.890 --> 00:24:39.190
They can just take their
replay and on-demand service,

00:24:39.190 --> 00:24:40.330
and watch it.

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:44.680
However, we believe
that users still love

00:24:44.680 --> 00:24:47.080
what linear TV has to offer.

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:49.180
If you turn on your
TV, you can be passive.

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:51.010
You get some moving images.

00:24:51.010 --> 00:24:55.010
You enjoy the
serendipity of discovery.

00:24:55.010 --> 00:24:57.640
And you also enjoy the
fluidity of the experience.

00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:00.730
As a result, as an
on-demand content provider,

00:25:00.730 --> 00:25:03.340
you should think
about all the ways

00:25:03.340 --> 00:25:09.850
you can recreate certain aspects
of this linear experience

00:25:09.850 --> 00:25:12.910
by adding functionality,
such as watch next, that

00:25:12.910 --> 00:25:16.630
are famously at the
origin of binge watching,

00:25:16.630 --> 00:25:17.800
related content.

00:25:17.800 --> 00:25:21.610
But also picture-in-picture and
background playing and animated

00:25:21.610 --> 00:25:22.570
carousel.

00:25:22.570 --> 00:25:25.630
All this functionality
really makes the experience

00:25:25.630 --> 00:25:28.010
within your app linear again.

00:25:31.150 --> 00:25:34.930
Last but not least,
obviously, payments.

00:25:34.930 --> 00:25:38.470
With the rise of millennials
and cord cutters,

00:25:38.470 --> 00:25:41.230
many media partners
have launched

00:25:41.230 --> 00:25:45.220
their own what are called
direct-to-consumer experiences

00:25:45.220 --> 00:25:45.790
and service.

00:25:45.790 --> 00:25:48.250
Which means that now,
all these partners

00:25:48.250 --> 00:25:53.350
need to handle the
payments directly.

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:56.980
As mentioned earlier, more
than in any other form factor,

00:25:56.980 --> 00:26:00.250
friction on TV can
be prohibitive.

00:26:00.250 --> 00:26:02.740
Being such a critical step
of your user's journey,

00:26:02.740 --> 00:26:05.080
you really want to
make sure that payments

00:26:05.080 --> 00:26:09.400
is handled correctly and
is as simple as possible.

00:26:09.400 --> 00:26:12.550
By integrating with
Google Play billing,

00:26:12.550 --> 00:26:16.280
users can complete that
payment in only three clicks.

00:26:16.280 --> 00:26:20.240
They can benefit from having
already their details saved

00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:23.310
into the accounts, and
benefit from having

00:26:23.310 --> 00:26:25.600
the different options in
terms of form of payments,

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:29.870
including credit
cards, PayPal, and DCD.

00:26:29.870 --> 00:26:32.920
Subscription is a huge
opportunity for subscribers.

00:26:32.920 --> 00:26:36.850
And over the last
year, in Google Play,

00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:40.450
we've doubled our revenue
associated to subscription.

00:26:40.450 --> 00:26:42.970
As a consequence, we've
multiplied the number

00:26:42.970 --> 00:26:46.030
of useful tools
and functionality

00:26:46.030 --> 00:26:47.920
inside the console
in order to manage

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:50.230
for you the subscription.

00:26:50.230 --> 00:26:53.440
Subscription Dashboard, that
was presented yesterday.

00:26:53.440 --> 00:26:55.420
Flexible payment periods.

00:26:55.420 --> 00:26:57.100
And of course,
promotional tools.

00:26:57.100 --> 00:27:00.220
That includes intro
pricing and free trial.

00:27:00.220 --> 00:27:02.470
All these [INAUDIBLE]
should, again,

00:27:02.470 --> 00:27:05.800
remove the friction
within the TV experience

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:06.850
to execute the payments.

